{"title_page": "Pro All Stars Series", "text_new": "{{Infobox motorsport championship\n| name            =Pro All Star Series\n| logo            =File:Pass chaudiere 180513 b.jpg\n| image-size      =300px\n| caption         =\n| category        =[[Stock car racing|Stock cars]]\n| country/region  ={{flag|Canada|size=23px}}<br />{{flag|United States}}\n| inaugural       =2001\n| inaugural2      =\n| folded          =\n| drivers         =\n| teams           =\n| constructors    =\n| engines         =\n| tires           =\n| champion driver =North \u2013 D.J. Shaw<br>National - Derek Griffith<br>Mods - Spencer Morse\n| website         ={{URL|http://www.proallstarsseries.com/|Pro All Star Series}}\n| current_season  =2017 Pro All Star Series\n}}\n\nThe '''Pro All Stars Series''' is a [[stock car racing]] governing body active in the [[United States of America]] and [[Canada]]. The series started in 2001 and now sanctions various series including North, South, and National Super Late Model tours and a New England Modified tour.\n\n==History==\nThe Pro All Stars Series started with the PASS North [[Late model|Pro Stock]] in 2001. The class was founded by former stockcar racer Tom Mayberry. The series was a successor to the [[Northeast Pro Stock Association]] and [[International Pro Stock Challenge]]. The first race was held on 20 May 2001 at [[Lee USA Speedway]]. [[Jim McCallum]] qualified his car on pole position. [[Dale Shaw]] beat his 32 rivals in the race over 150 laps.<ref>{{cite web|title=2001 Lee USA 150|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/2001_Lee_USA_150|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> [[Ben Rowe]] won six out of ten races in the season. But due to steady top five finishes [[Sam Sessions (racing driver)|Sam Sessions]] was the first series champion. Rowe won the next two titles in the series.\n\nFor 2004 a new raceclass was introduced. A 'touring style' [[Modified stock car racing|modified racing]] series started at [[White Mountain Motorsports Park]] with ten drivers starting the race. PASS regular Ben Rowe won the first race of the series.<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Modified:2004-01|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_Modified:2004-01|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> A further two years later PASS founded the Super Late Model Touring Series South. The series, founded in 2006, was based in [[North Carolina]] but also raced on tracks in [[South Carolina]], [[Virginia]] and other [[Southern United States|southern states]].\n\nNot all ventures of the Pro All Stars Series were highly successful. The PASS Outlaw Late Model series existed for three seasons. The championship was introduced as a breeding ground for new drivers before growing into the Super Late Models. The 2008 season saw very small grids. Nine drivers started the race at [[Speedway 95]], twelve drivers started the race at [[Riverside International Speedway|Riverside Speedway]]. Mayberry stated that the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|economic situation]] and the fact that other local tracks added the outlaw late model class contributed to the small field in the PASS Outlaw Late Models. Therefore Mayberry decided to cancel the season after two races.<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Cancels Balance of 2008 Outlaw Series Schedule|url=http://www.proallstarsseries.com/2-start-OUTLAW_Late_Models.htm|website=Pro All Stars Series|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> The PASS Late Model Truck Series was also short lived. The trucks were a support category to the PASS South Super Late Models on short tracks throughout North Carolina. With only six drivers at [[Southern National Raceway Park]] the PASS organisation decided to cancel the series with one round at [[Greenville-Pickens Speedway]] remaining.<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Late Model Truck  Season Complete;  Davidson Crowned Champion|url=http://www.proallstarsseries.com/SOUTH-HOME-2009.htm|website=Pro All Stars Series|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2012 Mayberry bought the historic [[Oxford Plains Speedway]]. The track changed its focus from [[American Canadian Tour]] Late Model sanctioning to the PASS Super Late Model sanctioning. This also affected the showcase race at Oxford Plains, the Oxford 250. As of 2013 the race run under PASS rules and is a point-scoring race for the PASS North and National championships.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oxford Plains Speedway sold|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2012/10/14/sports/oxford-plains-speedway-sold/|website=Bangor Daily News|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Champions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! {{Tooltip|North|PASS North Super Late Models}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS North Super Late Model Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_North_Super_Late_Model_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> !! {{Tooltip|South|PASS South Super Late Models}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS South Super Late Model Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_South_Super_Late_Model_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> !! {{Tooltip|National|PASS National Super Late Model Series}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS National Championship Super Late Model Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_National_Championship_Super_Late_Model_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> !! {{Tooltip|Modified|PASS Modified Series}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Modified Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_Modified_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> !! {{Tooltip|Northeast LMS|PASS Northeast Late Model Series}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Northeast Late Model Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_Northeast_Late_Model_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> !! {{Tooltip|Pro Late Model|PASS Pro Late Model Series}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Pro Late Model Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_Pro_Late_Model_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> !! {{Tooltip|Sportsman|PASS Sportsman Series}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Sportsman Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_Sportsman_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> !! {{Tooltip|Northwest SLM|PASS Northwest Super Late Model Triple Crown Series}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Northwest Super Late Model Triple Crown Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_Northwest_Super_Late_Model_Triple_Crown_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>  !! {{Tooltip|Outlaw|PASS Outlaw Late Model Series}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Outlaw Late Model Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_Outlaw_Late_Model_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> !! {{Tooltip|Trucks|PASS Late Model Truck Series}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Late Model Truck Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_Late_Model_Truck_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2001 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Sam Sessions ||  ||  ||  ||  || ||  ||  ||  ||\n|-\n|2002 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ben Rowe ||  ||  || ||  ||  || ||  || ||\n|-\n| 2003 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ben Rowe ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || ||  ||  ||\n|-\n| 2004 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Johnny Clark  ||  ||  || {{flagicon|Maine}} Mark Lucas ||  ||  || ||  || || \n|-\n| 2005 ||{{flagicon|Maine}} Ben Rowe ||  ||  || {{flagicon|Maine}} Wayne Allard ||  ||  ||  ||  || || \n|-\n| 2006 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Johnny Clark || {{flagicon|Maine}} [[Mike Rowe (racing)|Mike Rowe]] ||  || {{flagicon|Maine}} Chris Staples || || ||  ||  || {{flagicon|Massachusetts}} Derek Ramstrom ||\n|-\n| 2007 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ben Rowe || {{flagicon|Texas}} Ryan Lawler ||  || {{flagicon|Maine}} Chris Staples ||  ||  || {{flagicon|Maine}} Dan McKeage ||  || {{flagicon|Massachusetts}} Jimmy Rosenfield ||\n|-\n| 2008 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Johnny Clark || {{flagicon|Nevada}} Alex Haase || {{flagicon|Maine}}  Cassius Clark || {{flagicon|Maine}} Mark Lucas ||  ||  || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ricky Morse ||  || {{flagicon|Maine}} Mike Harnish ||\n|-\n| 2009 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Johnny Clark  || {{flagicon|Maine}}  Ben Rowe || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ben Rowe || {{flagicon|Maine}} Scott Grant  ||  ||  ||{{flagicon|Maine}} Carey Martin ||  || || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Grand Davidson\n|-\n| 2010 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Johnny Clark || {{flagicon|California}} Preston Peltier || {{flagicon|California}} Preston Peltier || {{flagicon|New Hampshire}}  Andy Shaw ||  ||  || {{flagicon|Maine}} Dan McKeage || ||  || \n|-\n| 2011 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Johnny Clark || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} [[Ryan Blaney]] || {{flagicon|Maine}}  Ben Rowe || {{flagicon|New Hampshire}} Andy Shaw ||  ||  ||{{flagicon|Maine}} Carey Martin ||  || || \n|-\n| 2012 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Travis Benjamin || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Kyle Grissom ||{{flagicon|North Carolina}} Jay Fogleman|| {{flagicon|New Hampshire}} Andy Shaw ||  || {{flagicon|South Carolina}} Austin Leitner ||{{flagicon|Maine}} Carey Martin ||  || || \n|-\n| 2013 || {{flagicon|Maine}} Cassius Clark || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Jay Fogleman || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Jay Fogleman || {{flagicon|Maine}} Scott Alexander ||  || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Trevor Noles ||{{flagicon|Maine}} Carey Martin || {{flagicon|Washington}} Garrett Evans || || \n|-\n| 2014 || {{flagicon|New Hampshire}} D.J. Shaw || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Tyler Church || {{flagicon|Maine}}  Ben Rowe || {{flagicon|New Hampshire}} Andy Shaw || {{flagicon|Maine}} Bradley Babb || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Walker Yates || {{flagicon|Maine}} Joe Pastore ||  || ||\n|-\n| 2015|| {{flagicon|Maine}}  [[Mike Rowe (racing)|Mike Rowe]] || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Tate Fogleman || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ben Rowe || {{flagicon|New Hampshire}} Andy Shaw ||  || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Kodie Conner ||  ||  ||  || \n|-\n| 2016|| {{flagicon|New Hampshire}} D.J. Shaw || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Matt Craig || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ben Rowe || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ryan Robbins ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|-\n| 2017|| {{flagicon|Maine}} Travis Benjamin|| {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Matt Craig || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ben Rowe || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ben Tinker || || || || || ||\n|-\n| 2018 || {{flagicon|New Hampshire}} D.J. Shaw || {{flagicon|North Carolina}} Matt Craig  ||{{flagicon|New Hampshire}} Derek Griffith || {{flagicon|Maine}} Ben Tinker || || || || || ||\n|-\n| 2019 ||{{flagicon|New Hampshire}} D.J. Shaw || || || {{flagicon|Maine}} Spencer Morse || || || || || ||\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.proallstarsseries.com/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:Auto racing series in Canada]]\n[[Category:Stock car racing series in the United States]]\n[[Category:Stock car racing]]\n[[Category:Motorsport in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox motorsport championship\n| name            =Pro All Star Series\n| logo            =File:Pass chaudiere 180513 b.jpg\n| image-size      =300px\n| caption         =\n| category        =[[Stock car racing|Stock cars]]\n| country/region  ={{flag|Canada|size=23px}}<br />{{flag|United States}}\n| inaugural       =2001\n| inaugural2      =\n| folded          =\n| drivers         =\n| teams           =\n| constructors    =\n| engines         =\n| tires           =\n| champion driver =North \u2013 D.J. Shaw<br>National - Derek Griffith<br>Mods - Spencer Morse\n| website         ={{URL|http://www.proallstarsseries.com/|Pro All Star Series}}\n| current_season  =2017 Pro All Star Series\n}}\n\nThe '''Pro All Stars Series''' is a [[stock car racing]] governing body active in the [[United States of America]] and [[Canada]]. The series started in 2001 and now sanctions various series including North, South, and National Super Late Model tours and a New England Modified tour.\n\n==History==\nThe Pro All Stars Series started with the PASS North [[Late model|Pro Stock]] in 2001. The class was founded by former stockcar racer Tom Mayberry. The series was a successor to the [[Northeast Pro Stock Association]] and [[International Pro Stock Challenge]]. The first race was held on 20 May 2001 at [[Lee USA Speedway]]. [[Jim McCallum]] qualified his car on pole position. [[Dale Shaw]] beat his 32 rivals in the race over 150 laps.<ref>{{cite web|title=2001 Lee USA 150|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/2001_Lee_USA_150|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> [[Ben Rowe]] won six out of ten races in the season. But due to steady top five finishes [[Sam Sessions (racing driver)|Sam Sessions]] was the first series champion. Rowe won the next two titles in the series.\n\nFor 2004 a new raceclass was introduced. A 'touring style' [[Modified stock car racing|modified racing]] series started at [[White Mountain Motorsports Park]] with ten drivers starting the race. PASS regular Ben Rowe won the first race of the series.<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Modified:2004-01|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_Modified:2004-01|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> A further two years later PASS founded the Super Late Model Touring Series South. The series, founded in 2006, was based in [[North Carolina]] but also raced on tracks in [[South Carolina]], [[Virginia]] and other [[Southern United States|southern states]].\n\nNot all ventures of the Pro All Stars Series were highly successful. The PASS Outlaw Late Model series existed for three seasons. The championship was introduced as a breeding ground for new drivers before growing into the Super Late Models. The 2008 season saw very small grids. Nine drivers started the race at [[Speedway 95]], twelve drivers started the race at [[Riverside International Speedway|Riverside Speedway]]. Mayberry stated that the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|economic situation]] and the fact that other local tracks added the outlaw late model class contributed to the small field in the PASS Outlaw Late Models. Therefor Mayberry decided to cancel the season after two races.<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Cancels Balance of 2008 Outlaw Series Schedule|url=http://www.proallstarsseries.com/2-start-OUTLAW_Late_Models.htm|website=Pro All Stars Series|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> The PASS Late Model Truck Series was also short lived. The trucks were a support category to the PASS South Super Late Models on short tracks throughout North Carolina. With only six drivers at [[Southern National Raceway Park]] the PASS organisation decided to cancel the series with one round at [[Greenville-Pickens Speedway]] remaining.<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS Late Model Truck  Season Complete;  Davidson Crowned Champion|url=http://www.proallstarsseries.com/SOUTH-HOME-2009.htm|website=Pro All Stars Series|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2012 Mayberry bought the historic [[Oxford Plains Speedway]]. The track changed its focus from [[American Canadian Tour]] Late Model sanctioning to the PASS Super Late Model sanctioning. This also affected the showcase race at Oxford Plains, the Oxford 250. As of 2013 the race run under PASS rules and is a point-scoring race for the PASS North and National championships.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oxford Plains Speedway sold|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2012/10/14/sports/oxford-plains-speedway-sold/|website=Bangor Daily News|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Champions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! {{Tooltip|North|PASS North Super Late Models}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS North Super Late Model Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_North_Super_Late_Model_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> !! {{Tooltip|South|PASS South Super Late Models}}<ref>{{cite web|title=PASS South Super Late Model Series|url=http://www.thethirdturn.com/wiki/PASS_South_Super_Late_Model_Series_Central|website=The Third Turn|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> !! {{Tooltip|Natio